// Template: iterative scientific-research consensus with a variable
// roster of providers.
//
// Shape:
//
//   Phase 1 (parallel, one per reviewer): each reviewer reads the
//     problem file ({{PROBLEM_FILE}}) plus any optional local material
//     under {{DATA_DIR}} / {{LOCAL_LIT_DIR}}, performs extensive
//     independent literature research via web tools, and writes
//     (a) a conclusion document and (b) an evidence log. Reviewers do
//     NOT read each other's work in this phase — the point is an
//     independent baseline.
//
//   Phase 2 (loop up to 10): each reviewer reads every peer's prior
//     conclusion + summary + evidence, performs ADDITIONAL targeted web
//     research, and writes a new conclusion, comparison summary, and
//     evidence log. After each pass `convergence-judge` (sonnet)
//     classifies the iteration; the loop exits on PASS after `stability`
//     consecutive passes, or hits `max_iterations 10`.
//
// Roster:
//
//   The reviewer panel is a workflow parameter — supplied via
//   `--param roster=...`. The in-script default below runs the same
//   three-provider panel (Claude Opus + Codex GPT-5.5 + Cursor Composer)
//   the legacy template used. Each roster entry is
//   `id=provider:model[@effort]`; the id becomes the filename prefix
//   and the model + effort bind the cloned reviewer agent to an
//   anonymous client. Use distinct ids per reviewer.
//
// Files written per iteration N (N=1 for init, N=2..11 for refinement):
//
//   {{OUT_DIR}}/<id>-conclusion-v{N}.md      (init + every refine pass)
//   {{OUT_DIR}}/<id>-summary-v{N}.md         (refine only — iteration metadata)
//   {{OUT_DIR}}/<id>-evidence-v{N}.md        (init + every refine pass — audit log)
//
// Conclusion / summary / evidence contract:
//   - conclusion: standalone hand-off document. No peer ids, no
//     version numbers, no iteration narrative. Pure deliverable.
//   - summary: every iteration-meta lives here — convergence status,
//     comparison findings, what changed, what was rejected, remaining
//     research questions. The judge's cheap path reads only summaries.
//   - evidence: search strategy, sources, claim-to-source mapping. The
//     audit trail; never read by the judge but available for borderline
//     escalation and for the human handoff at the end.
//
// Inputs (set via --var):
//   PROBLEM_FILE  — markdown file with the problem statement, data
//                   references, prior results, and success criteria.
//                   The {{PROMPT}} CLI argument is treated as a short
//                   topic title; the substantive description lives in
//                   this file so every reviewer anchors to the same
//                   source of truth. (default: research_problem.md)
//   OUT_DIR       — directory for all generated files. (default: research)
//   DATA_DIR      — optional local data directory, read-only for every
//                   reviewer. May be empty or non-existent. (default: data)
//   LOCAL_LIT_DIR — optional local literature directory, read-only for
//                   every reviewer. May be empty. (default: literature)
//
// Cost note:
//   Multiple frontier providers x up to 10 refinement passes plus init
//   is expensive — easily 30+ deep-reasoning turns for a 3-reviewer
//   panel. Convergence via the judge is the only way to exit early;
//   the prompts deliberately push reviewers to declare consensus
//   honestly once substantive disagreements close. `stability 2`
//   guards against a flaky single PASS verdict.
//
// Usage:
//
//   Default 3-provider panel:
//     gaviero-cli --script crates/gaviero-dsl/examples/scientific_research.gaviero \
//       --prompt "Short topic title for logs" \
//       --var PROBLEM_FILE=research_problem.md \
//       --var OUT_DIR=research
//
//   Custom 2-provider panel:
//     gaviero-cli --script crates/gaviero-dsl/examples/scientific_research.gaviero \
//       --prompt "Short topic title for logs" \
//       --var PROBLEM_FILE=research_problem.md \
//       --param roster=claude=claude:opus@max,codex=codex:gpt-5.5@high

// ── Shared configuration ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// PROBLEM_FILE: external problem statement. {{PROMPT}} from the CLI is
// the short title; the substantive description lives in this file.
//
// DATA_DIR / LOCAL_LIT_DIR: optional local context. When the directories
// don't exist or are empty, agents fall back to web research + the
// problem file. The defaults match the conventional layout but are
// fully overridable.
//
// INIT_VER: the version written by the init phase; read by the first
// loop pass as PREV_ITER (iter_start 2 -> PREV_ITER=1 on iteration 1).

vars {
    OUT_DIR       "research"
    INIT_VER      "1"
    PROBLEM_FILE  "research_problem.md"
    DATA_DIR      "data"
    LOCAL_LIT_DIR "literature"
}

// ── Prompts ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// Three prompts:
//   - init-body:     independent first pass, conclusion + evidence
//   - refine-body:   peer-aware refinement, conclusion + summary + evidence
//   - judge-body:    two-pass convergence judgement
//
// All three reference {{REVIEWER_ID}} (the roster entry id),
// {{PEER_IDS}} / {{PEER_COUNT}} / {{PEER_READ_BLOCK}} (peer enumeration
// auto-substituted by the roster expansion), and the runtime
// {{ITER}} / {{PREV_ITER}} / {{ITER_EVIDENCE}} substitutions.

prompt init-body #"
    You are an independent senior scientific research strategist.

    Short topic title: {{PROMPT}}
    Full problem statement: {{PROBLEM_FILE}}

    Optional local material:
      - Data:              {{DATA_DIR}}/
      - Local literature:  {{LOCAL_LIT_DIR}}/
    These directories may not exist or may be empty — treat them as
    optional. When absent, focus on web research and the problem file.

    1. Read {{PROBLEM_FILE}} in full. Treat it as the authoritative
       description of the endeavour — the available data, the existing
       results, the constraints, and what success looks like. Do NOT
       paraphrase loosely; every downstream conclusion you draw must
       trace back to something in that file.

    2. Inspect {{DATA_DIR}}/ and {{LOCAL_LIT_DIR}}/ for relevant local
       material. Treat any local data as evidence to be characterised,
       not as proof. If a directory does not exist, skip it.

    3. Do NOT read any peer outputs (other reviewers' conclusion /
       summary / evidence files) under {{OUT_DIR}}/. This is the
       independent first pass; peer analyses arrive only in the refine
       phase. Reading {{PROBLEM_FILE}} is fine even when it lives
       inside {{OUT_DIR}}/.

    4. Conduct EXTENSIVE current web research using every web search
       and fetch tool available to you. Prioritise:
         - peer-reviewed papers, preprints, datasets, benchmarks,
           standards, and reputable technical reports;
         - literature from the last 24–36 months when the field is
           active; include seminal older work only where it materially
           changes the analysis;
         - leading research groups, dominant techniques, recent
           surprises, and the open questions;
         - negative results, reproducibility issues, retractions, and
           evidence that weakens attractive hypotheses;
         - the citation graph two hops deep where something seems
           load-bearing.

       Do NOT skip this step. The workflow's whole point is that each
       provider brings a fresh, well-sourced literature view;
       superficial research undermines the comparison phase.

    5. Think from first principles AFTER the research, not before. The
       literature constrains what's been tried and what failed;
       first-principles thinking constrains what's plausible under the
       {{PROBLEM_FILE}} constraints. Combine them.

    Hard rules:
      - Be critical, honest, and specific. State your real best
        assessment, including where you think the problem may be
        ill-posed or where the available data is likely insufficient.
      - Distinguish what is known from what is inferred.
      - Do NOT invent citations, datasets, or results. If web tools are
        unavailable, state that explicitly in the evidence log and rely
        only on local material.
      - Do NOT optimise for agreement; optimise for truth and for
        useful next research actions.

    Write TWO files.

    File 1 — the conclusion:
      {{OUT_DIR}}/{{REVIEWER_ID}}-conclusion-v{{INIT_VER}}.md

    It must contain exactly these sections, in this order:
      - `## Problem understanding`
      - `## Current evidence base`
      - `## Best avenues for advance`
      - `## Critical risks and failure modes`
      - `## Data and literature gaps`
      - `## Proposed research programme`
      - `## Decision points and stopping criteria`

    Requirements for File 1:
      - Rank the best avenues for advance.
      - For each avenue, state the central hypothesis, evidence
        needed, expected upside, main risks, first decisive experiment
        or analysis, and stopping criteria.
      - Include explicit reasons why attractive avenues may fail.
      - Decision points and stopping criteria must be specific enough
        to act on — e.g. "abandon if SNR < 3σ on dataset X" rather
        than "abandon if results are weak".

    File 2 — the evidence log:
      {{OUT_DIR}}/{{REVIEWER_ID}}-evidence-v{{INIT_VER}}.md

    It must contain exactly these sections, in this order:
      - `## Search strategy`
      - `## Sources reviewed`
      - `## Evidence extracted`
      - `## Claims needing verification`
      - `## Research limitations`

    Requirements for File 2:
      - List the search queries and discovery paths used.
      - For each source, include title, authors (when available),
        venue/source, year/date, URL or DOI, and the specific claim it
        supports or weakens.
      - Mark each source as `local`, `web`, `peer-reviewed`,
        `preprint`, `dataset`, `standard`, or `report` when possible.

    Aim for depth over breadth. A 3000-word conclusion engaging
    seriously with 15 sources beats a 1500-word conclusion name-dropping
    50.
"#

prompt refine-body #"
    You are refining your independent scientific research conclusion.

    Short topic title: {{PROMPT}}
    Full problem statement: {{PROBLEM_FILE}}
    Optional local material: {{DATA_DIR}}/ and {{LOCAL_LIT_DIR}}/

    There are {{PEER_COUNT}} other reviewers in this iteration: {{PEER_IDS}}.
    Your reviewer id is {{REVIEWER_ID}}.

    Inputs to read this pass:

    1. Re-read {{PROBLEM_FILE}} in full. The problem statement is the
       anchor — every conclusion must trace back to a constraint,
       datum, or goal listed there.

    2. Read your own previous work:
         - {{OUT_DIR}}/{{REVIEWER_ID}}-conclusion-v{{PREV_ITER}}.md
         - {{OUT_DIR}}/{{REVIEWER_ID}}-evidence-v{{PREV_ITER}}.md
       When {{PREV_ITER}} >= 2, also re-read your previous summary:
         - {{OUT_DIR}}/{{REVIEWER_ID}}-summary-v{{PREV_ITER}}.md

    3. Read every peer's previous work IN FULL.

{{PEER_READ_BLOCK}}

       Additionally, for each peer id in {{PEER_IDS}}, read
         {{OUT_DIR}}/<peer>-evidence-v{{PREV_ITER}}.md
       so you can verify the sources behind their claims. (The
       generated list above shows conclusion + summary; the evidence
       log lives under the same `-evidence-v{{PREV_ITER}}.md` suffix.)

    4. Conduct ADDITIONAL targeted web research this iteration. Do NOT
       merely repeat the searches from the previous pass. Specifically:
         - Read primary sources peers cited that you did not. If a peer
           grounds a claim in a paper outside your prior bibliography,
           fetch and read that paper before evaluating their argument.
         - Look for newer publications (preprints in the last six
           months — the field moves fast).
         - Search for counter-evidence to the strongest claims in your
           previous conclusion. Specifically try to falsify your own
           strongest conclusion.
         - Follow up on any "I'd want to check X" notes from prior
           summaries.

       Each refinement pass MUST be backed by fresh searches, not just
       re-reading the prior trio. A refinement that adds no new sources
       adds no new signal — the whole point of iterating is to deepen
       the evidence base.

    Then synthesise:

    5. Evaluate every peer's conclusion on its merits. For each peer
       in {{PEER_IDS}}:
         - Strongest claim — and whether the literature supports it.
         - Weakest claim — and what evidence would change your mind.
         - What this peer saw that you did not (techniques, risks,
           sources, framings).
         - What this peer overlooked or got wrong, citing sources.

    6. Decide whether the panel has converged. Convergence means every
       reviewer's analysis agrees on:
         - the framing of the problem;
         - the top two or three avenues for advance (the same
           directions, not necessarily the same priority ordering);
         - the dominant risks and failure modes;
         - the evidence required to validate or falsify the top
           avenues;
         - the decision points and stopping criteria.

       Editorial differences (wording, section length, which extra
       sources are cited beyond a shared core) DO NOT block convergence.

         - **If the panel has converged**: do NOT introduce new
           directions, risks, or analytical frames just to make
           progress visible. Copy your previous conclusion
           ({{OUT_DIR}}/{{REVIEWER_ID}}-conclusion-v{{PREV_ITER}}.md)
           into v{{ITER}} verbatim — same sections, same prose, same
           bibliography. Byte stability across iterations is the
           desired outcome. Declare convergence in the summary (step
           8). Do not converge for social reasons.

         - **If the panel has NOT converged**: synthesise a new
           conclusion taking the strongest evidence-backed elements
           from your prior conclusion AND from the peer conclusions,
           and resolve conflicts on their merits. Make the minimum
           changes needed to close the actual gaps — do not invent
           additional refinements beyond what the disagreements demand.

    Outputs to write this pass — THREE files.

    7. The conclusion:
       {{OUT_DIR}}/{{REVIEWER_ID}}-conclusion-v{{ITER}}.md

       Exactly these sections, in this order:
         - `## Problem understanding`
         - `## Current evidence base`
         - `## Best avenues for advance`
         - `## Critical risks and failure modes`
         - `## Data and literature gaps`
         - `## Proposed research programme`
         - `## Decision points and stopping criteria`

       Same shape as the init body — this is the document a human
       reviewer would read at the end of the run. Hard rules — failing
       any of these makes the conclusion unfit for hand-off:
         - Present your current best conclusion as a standalone
           document. Rank the avenues for advance. For each avenue,
           state hypothesis, evidence needed, expected upside, main
           risks, first decisive experiment or analysis, and stopping
           criteria.
         - Do NOT write "I previously said X but now…", "peer Y
           proposed Z which I reject…", or any first-person iteration
           narrative.
         - Do NOT reference peer ids, version numbers (v{{PREV_ITER}},
           v{{ITER}}), or refinement passes anywhere in the conclusion
           body.
         - Do NOT include `## Synthesis Notes`, `## Comparison`, or
           any other iteration-metadata section in the conclusion.

       All iteration metadata, peer comparison, and version references
       belong in the summary file (step 8) — never the conclusion.

    8. The comparison summary:
       {{OUT_DIR}}/{{REVIEWER_ID}}-summary-v{{ITER}}.md

       Keep it under ~900 words. Use these sections, in this order:
         - `## Consensus status` — the very first sentence MUST be
           EXACTLY one of these two strings, with no other content
           before it:
              `Consensus reached.`
              `Consensus not reached.`
           The judge keys off that exact phrasing for its cheap
           summary-only pass. If this version is a no-material-change
           convergence copy, write `Consensus reached.` and add a
           second sentence stating which previous version you copied
           verbatim (e.g. "Copied conclusion-v{{PREV_ITER}} into
           v{{ITER}} unchanged."). Otherwise write `Consensus not
           reached.` and one sentence describing the dominant
           remaining disagreement.
         - `## Merits of each proposal` — one short subsection per
           peer id in {{PEER_IDS}}. For each: what you adopted from
           them, what you rejected, what specific evidence drove the
           adjudication. Cite sources.
         - `## Substantive disagreements` — disagreements that are
           about substance (avenues, risks, evidence required,
           stopping criteria), not wording. Empty list if converged.
         - `## Changes made in this iteration` — what you changed in
           your conclusion this pass and why. If you copied the
           previous version verbatim, say so here too.
         - `## Remaining research questions` — the disagreements you
           expect the next iteration to address. Empty list if
           converged.

       Write the summary for a human skimming the iteration evolution.

    9. The evidence log:
       {{OUT_DIR}}/{{REVIEWER_ID}}-evidence-v{{ITER}}.md

       Exactly these sections, in this order:
         - `## New search strategy`
         - `## New or revalidated sources`
         - `## Evidence extracted`
         - `## Claims strengthened`
         - `## Claims weakened`
         - `## Research limitations`

       Requirements:
         - Include the search queries and discovery paths used this
           iteration.
         - For each source, include title, authors (when available),
           venue/source, year/date, URL or DOI, and the specific
           claim it supports or weakens.
         - Clearly mark sources as newly discovered or revalidated.
"#

prompt judge-body #"
    You are deciding whether a panel of independently refined scientific
    research conclusions has reached consensus for:

    Topic:             {{PROMPT}}
    Problem statement: {{PROBLEM_FILE}}

    {{ITER_EVIDENCE}}

    The digest above lists what the refine agents actually changed
    this iteration. Use it to focus your reading — if a file is not
    listed there it did not change this pass.

    Evaluate in two passes — start cheap, only escalate to the full
    conclusion documents on borderline calls. Reading every conclusion
    for every reviewer each iteration is expensive; the summaries
    exist precisely so this pass can usually settle on summaries alone.

    Pass 1 (cheap, always do this):

    1. Read every reviewer's summary for iteration {{ITER}}. The files
       live under {{OUT_DIR}}/ and match the glob:
         {{OUT_DIR}}/*-summary-v{{ITER}}.md
       Each summary is ≤ ~900 words and carries the convergence
       status, comparison findings, changes, and remaining open
       questions for this pass.

    2. From the summaries alone, classify the iteration:

       - **Convergence shortcut — PASS**: EVERY summary's first
         sentence is exactly `Consensus reached.`. A single dissenting
         summary blocks PASS. If every reviewer declared consensus,
         stop here and return PASS.

       - **Material divergence shortcut — FAIL**: any summary
         describes a material change to the problem framing, the top
         avenues for advance, the dominant risks, the evidence
         required to validate or falsify those avenues, or the
         decision points / stopping criteria. Stop here and return
         FAIL.

       - **Borderline**: continue to Pass 2.

    Pass 2 (deep, only on borderline):

    3. Read every reviewer's conclusion for iteration {{ITER}}:
         {{OUT_DIR}}/*-conclusion-v{{ITER}}.md

    4. If you still need it, compare against the v{{PREV_ITER}}
       conclusions to judge whether a specific difference is material.

    5. Return PASS if the conclusions substantively agree on:
         - the ranked best avenues for advance;
         - the critical risks and failure modes;
         - the evidence required to validate or falsify the top
           avenues;
         - the data and literature gaps that matter most;
         - the decision points and stopping criteria.
       Wording differences and extra citations beyond a shared core
       DO NOT block convergence — they are expected artefacts of
       independent literature reviews.

    6. Otherwise return FAIL.

    Output format — emit exactly one fenced JSON object as your last
    output. Keep the reason terse (one short sentence) so the response
    fits inside the judge timeout:

    ```json
    {"verdict": "pass" | "fail", "reason": "<one short sentence>"}
    ```

    A plain `VERDICT: PASS` / `VERDICT: FAIL` line is also accepted as
    a fallback, but the JSON form is preferred for machine
    parseability.
"#

// ── Agents ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// Two reviewer templates (init and refine) plus a fixed convergence
// judge. The init / refine templates are cloned per roster entry by
// the loop expansion in crates/gaviero-dsl/src/reviewers.rs:
//
//   - {{REVIEWER_ID}} is substituted with each entry's id in the
//     description, scope paths, and prompt body.
//   - Each clone is bound to an anonymous client carrying that entry's
//     model + effort.
//   - Refine clones additionally get {{PEER_IDS}}, {{PEER_COUNT}}, and
//     {{PEER_READ_BLOCK}} substituted for cross-reviewer prompting.
//
// Init agents deliberately do NOT have {{OUT_DIR}}/ in their read_only
// scope — they form an independent baseline and the prompt forbids
// reading peer outputs. Refine agents do read {{OUT_DIR}}/.

agent reviewer-init {
    template true
    description "Initial scientific research analysis ({{REVIEWER_ID}}): {{PROMPT}}"
    tools ["WebSearch" "WebFetch"]
    scope {
        owned [
            "{{OUT_DIR}}/{{REVIEWER_ID}}-conclusion-v*.md"
            "{{OUT_DIR}}/{{REVIEWER_ID}}-evidence-v*.md"
        ]
        read_only [
            "{{PROBLEM_FILE}}"
            "{{DATA_DIR}}/"
            "{{LOCAL_LIT_DIR}}/"
        ]
    }
    prompt init-body
    max_retries 1
}

agent reviewer-refine {
    template true
    description "Refine scientific research conclusion ({{REVIEWER_ID}}): {{PROMPT}}"
    tools ["WebSearch" "WebFetch"]
    scope {
        owned [
            "{{OUT_DIR}}/{{REVIEWER_ID}}-conclusion-v*.md"
            "{{OUT_DIR}}/{{REVIEWER_ID}}-summary-v*.md"
            "{{OUT_DIR}}/{{REVIEWER_ID}}-evidence-v*.md"
        ]
        read_only [
            "{{PROBLEM_FILE}}"
            "{{DATA_DIR}}/"
            "{{LOCAL_LIT_DIR}}/"
            "{{OUT_DIR}}/"
        ]
    }
    prompt refine-body
    max_retries 1
    memory {
        write_ns   "scientific-research-consensus"
        importance 0.8
        write_content #"
            Scientific research refinement for {{PROMPT}} anchored to {{PROBLEM_FILE}}.
        "#
    }
}

agent convergence-judge {
    description "Judge consensus across reviewer panel: {{PROMPT}}"
    client judge
    scope {
        read_only ["{{OUT_DIR}}/" "{{PROBLEM_FILE}}"]
    }
    prompt judge-body
    max_retries 1
}

// ── Workflow ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// The `roster` workflow parameter binds the loop's `reviewers` slot to
// a list of provider entries. Override entirely from the CLI:
//
//   --param roster=claude=claude:opus@max,codex=codex:gpt-5.5@high,cursor=cursor:composer-2.5@high
//
// The in-script default below runs the legacy three-provider panel
// (Claude Opus + Codex GPT-5.5 + Cursor Composer at maximum research
// depth) so the example works with no flag.
//
// Loop knobs:
//
//   stability 2       — require 2 consecutive PASS verdicts before
//                       exiting. A single PASS is treated as
//                       provisional; the refine agents run one more
//                       pass and the judge re-evaluates. Guards
//                       against a flaky "looks good" verdict on a
//                       panel that is still materially evolving.
//   judge_timeout 240 — hard cap each judge invocation at 240s (0
//                       disables). Wide enough that even the deep-read
//                       borderline path covering every reviewer's
//                       conclusion can finish.
//   strict_judge false — unparseable judge output is treated as FAIL
//                       rather than a hard error; a timeout on the
//                       final loop check cannot bury the run.
//   iter_start 2      — loop iteration 1 -> ITER=2, PREV_ITER=1
//                       (reads the v1 init files); subsequent passes
//                       increment by 1 up to ITER=11 at iteration 10.
//
// The judge prompt also uses {{ITER_EVIDENCE}}: the runtime substitutes
// a bounded digest of the refine agents' most recent summaries and
// modified files so the judge can focus on what actually changed.
//
// Post-convergence the workflow leaves one conclusion + summary +
// evidence triple per reviewer on disk for the iteration that
// converged. None is designated canonical here — the human operator
// picks one (or merges across reviewers) to hand off.
//
// max_parallel 5 supports rosters up to five reviewers running in
// parallel; the default 3-reviewer panel uses three of those slots.

workflow scientific-research-consensus {
    param judge {
        model "claude:sonnet"
        effort medium
    }
    param roster [
        { id "claude" model "claude:opus"         effort max  }
        { id "codex"  model "codex:gpt-5.5"       effort high }
        { id "cursor" model "cursor:composer-2.5" effort high }
    ]

    steps [
        loop {
            reviewers       roster
            template_init   reviewer-init
            template_refine reviewer-refine
            max_iterations  10
            iter_start      2
            stability       2
            judge_timeout   240
            strict_judge    false
            until agent     convergence-judge
        }
    ]
    max_parallel 5
    memory {
        write_ns "scientific-research-consensus"
    }
}
